  "prompt": "How will scraping of 500 and 1000 rupees notes help in curbing corruption and black money?",
  "response": "The demonetization of 500 and 1000 rupee notes in November 2016 was aimed at addressing black money and corruption through several mechanisms:\n\n1. Forcing declaration of unaccounted cash\n- People had to deposit or exchange old notes through banking channels\n- Suspicious large deposits were tracked by income tax authorities\n- Undeclared income became traceable\n\n2. Disrupting illicit cash transactions\n- Cash holdings beyond declared income became difficult to convert\n- Reduced immediate liquidity for corruption and illegal activities\n\n3. Digital transaction push\n- Encouraged digital payments and banking\n- Created more transparent financial trails\n- Reduced cash-based transactions prone to manipulation\n\n4. Curbing counterfeit currency\n- Eliminated existing fake currency notes in circulation\n- New notes had enhanced security features\n\n5. Reducing cash-based tax evasion\n- Increased financial transparency\n- Made it harder to maintain parallel cash economies\n\nHowever, the actual effectiveness of demonetization remains debated, with mixed economic and practical outcomes. While the intention was noble, implementation challenges and economic disruptions were significant.\n\nExperts have different perspectives on the overall impact, with some arguing the benefits were limited compared to the economic costs.\n\nThe long-term success in curbing corruption depends on sustained systemic reforms beyond a one-time monetary intervention.",
